The president of Brazil blames the industrial nations for perpetuating
the poverty of the developing nations.

In West Berlin, the finance ministers of 22 developed or developing
countries demanded action to help Third World countries with their 1.2
trillion dollar debt.

Brazil, the world's most indebted nation with 121 billion in foreign
loans, has been among the most vociferous lobbyists for debt
restructuring and write-offs.

There is an imbalance in trade. One group is selling its wares cheaply
and buying those of others dearly.

The seven key industrialized nations have approved a plan to aid the
world's poorest countries.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d30"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA091889-0088"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 

Third World debtors paid 50 billion dollars more last year than they
received in new loans just to service their debt.

Economic progress by the Third World has been mixed, from a mini- boom
in Southeast Asia to further impoverishment in Africa.

The figures on the cash drain from Third World countries are
mushrooming rapidly. This is a prime indicator of the strain that the
global debt is putting on the Third World. The debt of the Third World
is 993 billion dollars and growing. Greater efforts are needed by the
industrial nations to reduce Third World debt.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d30"
TYPE="PERDOC"
