Lord Bauer, House of Lords, makes the following comments to "Letters
to the Editor," Financial Times, from a Mr. Skinner:

a. Skinner charged Bauer with misunderstanding the debt burden of poor
countries. Bauer comments that the loans do not increase with
inflation and are at zero interest. Further, these loans are often
canceled or rescheduled.

b. Skinner claimed that Africa's poverty is externally-caused. Bauer
believes that it is domestically-caused by government policies.

c. Bauer believes that the poor are at the bottom of the priority list
of local rulers.

d.Skinner's encouragement of default is counter-productive. Bauer
points to the success of Southeast Asia.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d30"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900416-0188"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 

John Hatch happened upon a novel idea. His idea was something called
"village banking." This system is a means of investment using small
loans to poor women to finance their own private enterprise, e.g.,
selling produce, crafts, etc. This arrangement allows them to create
savings while paying interest and thereby qualifying for larger
loans. The "village banking" system has grown to nine countries.

Hatch says he created the system in order to channel money to the
poor, primarily the mothers of children who would otherwise starve to
death.

The women have a loan repayment rate of nearly 100 percent.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d30"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910607-0063"
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 

Unlike many conventional systems for making loans in the world, making
a microloan to a Third World small business entrepreneur is almost a
guarantee of repayment. Recipients want the security of a favorable
credit rating. These microloans cancel out the need to get involved
with loan sharks.

Third world banks and large development organizations are making such
loans as well, particularly when they discovered that the repayment
rate by the poor is nearly 100 percent.

Some charitable organizations still prefer to make per-to-person
sponsorships and the teaching of skills to improve the quality of
life.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d30"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT922-8860" 
SELECTOR="E"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 
	
Henceforth, the World Bank will tie loan volume to efforts by a
receiving country to fight poverty.  This new emphasis will make the
aim of alleviation of poverty a central objective by the bank in the
1990's.

The Bank said that poverty assessments by country will be available
within two years.  The assessments will allow the receiving country
and the World Bank to collaborate in a joint effort at poverty
reduction.

The new directive rewards a government with larger loans for a
stronger commitment to poverty reduction; a weaker commitment to
poverty reduction will warrant less support.</SUM>
